steps.name: London
steps.description: It's lights out and away we go, we're on our way to Sydney with a quick pit stop in Dubai.

steps.name: Dubai
steps.description:
To break up the journey (and save some money) we purposefully booked a flight with a 20 hour layover in Dubai. Through the Emirates Dubai Connect program we got a night in a hotel for free so we had a short nap and then got ready to explore a bit.

It was over 40c so even the short 8 minute walk to the Metro station was quite a challenge. We kept things fairly simple and went to the Dubai Mall to check out the aquarium, Burj Khalifa, fountain show and the air conditioning. The scale of everything in Dubai is pretty crazy and while we didn't get to see much of it was nice to experience a new country and culture, albeit briefly.

steps.name: Sydney
steps.description: Our first stop in Oz in s̶u̶n̶n̶y̶ Sydney. It’s not an exaggeration to say that it rained pretty much non-stop during our stay, so much so that we ran out of dry clothes. Between the rain and the jet lag we probably didn’t quite get the start to our trip we were expecting but we got out there and saw the main sights, safe in the knowledge we planned to return later in the year.

steps.name: Mount Remarkable National Park
steps.description:
Stop number 1 of our great Australian road trip! A few hours out of Adelaide, we spent a couple of nights camping in a national park. We were greeted with Kangaroos, Emus and Kookaburras wandering around camp, and so many stars in the sky at night!

We did a nice walk through the park, up to a viewpoint, and enjoyed the peace and quiet after a month or so in cities.

steps.name: Spud's Roadhouse
steps.description: Our first roadhouse and our first experience of quite how empty parts of the outback are. We met an interesting guy in the van parked next to us who showed us his opal collection, made some dinner on our stove and then had a few drinks inside to stay warm.

steps.name: Marla
steps.description: Another night on the road, another roadhouse stopover. To keep these balanced and not only containing the good stuff there we were besieged by flies here and learnt to perfect the Aussie wave.

steps.name: Erldunda Roadhouse
steps.description: Not too much to say about this, it was an overnight stop on our way to Alice Springs. They had a camel.

steps.name: Banka Banka
steps.description: A great little camp at a farm homestead. They had an Indian food truck which did a great paneer curry and roti, and music around the camp fire.

steps.name: Daly Waters
steps.description:
The Famous Daly Waters pub. We spend 2 night here in one of the motel rooms to refresh and get a chance to wash off some of the red dust that's accumulating.

Lots of interesting things around town, great garlic bread in the pub, and some great happy hour deals.

steps.name: Daly Waters
steps.description:
Since we were passing Daly Waters again on our way back down we decided to stop in for more garlic bread and $5 wines. This time we were treated to the eccentric owner on his mobility scooter telling us the history of the pub accompanied by his menagerie of animals.

It was up to 35 degrees during the day which made for a sweaty night's sleep. We went to bed to news of the Queen's deteriorating health and woke up to news of her death. A very strange place to be hearing the news.

steps.name: Karumba
steps.description: We started the day with no plans as to where to spend the night. On the drive James found a holiday park with  a caravan to rent available for the night, so we booked it and headed there. Turned out to be a very picturesque spot. We grabbed some fish and chips and watched the sunset before stopping in for a quick drink at the pub.

steps.name: Mackay
steps.description: Not much to say about this one, we arrived in town fairly late and stayed in a motel.

steps.name: Hervey Bay
steps.description: There was a jetty apparently, can’t remember much else. I’m writing this 6 months on, cut me some slack.

steps.name: Brisbane
steps.description: Overnight stay in a hotel (pub) before we flew out to Bali early the next morning.

steps.name: South Yarra
steps.description: Another house sit, just a short one this weekend with a very lazy goldendoodle called Penny. We dragged (quite literally sometimes) her out for a few walks and played some tennis. Explored South Yarra a little, probably one of the nicest Melbourne suburbs we’ve seen so far!

steps.name: Lynbrook
steps.description:
We had a couple of days to fill in-between house sits and managed to find a very reasonably priced BnB south east of Melbourne, it even came with two cats which was a nice bonus.

The main thing we did was visit the royal botanic gardens in Cranbourne which were very impressive.

steps.name: Black Rock
steps.description:
We had a very chilled week doing a house sit and looking after a very excitable young toy poodle called Jasper. We stayed in a really nice apartment that was literally on beach road on the coast south east of Melbourne.

We took Jasper out for lots of walks along the beach, did a bit of work and tried to plan where we were going next!

steps.name: Lynbrook
steps.description: Back in lynbrook at the same b&b again since it was cheap and very nice. Didn’t do much this time since it was just a quick overnighted before heading out into the mountains tomorrow.

steps.name: Ararat
steps.description: We had a couple of nights until we needed to be back in the city and found a cheap holiday cabin in this little town. Turned out to be a great stop - lovely park, nice tennis courts for a hit, and we did a cellar tour at a local winery that was really interesting! They claimed to be the birthplace of sparkling red wine.

steps.name: St Kilda
steps.description: Quick stop back in Melbourne to watch Maisie Peters in St Kilda, and see a woman about some cats. We spent a morning wandering Albert park where they’re currently building the track for next month’s Grand Prix. That’s the next time we’ll be back in the city!

steps.name: Jamieson Creek
steps.description: Just one night at a bush campsite but we caught a lovely sunset and watched the wallabies hop around camp. Woke up to one of Nicole’s sandals halfway across the site and all chewed up - maybe a possum?

steps.name: Dartmoor
steps.description: Just a quick overnight stop in Dartmoor in a free camping spot. The town is very small but had a nice pub and some interesting tree sculptures.

steps.name: Robe
steps.description: Beautiful little beach town on the limestone coast in south SA. Spent a few days relaxing and recharging after the great ocean road. The highlight of Robe was probably long beach (aptly named at around 12km long) where you can drive right along the sand and bag yourself a quiet spot with no one else around. Sunset over the water was spectacular.

steps.name: Haddon
steps.description: Just a quick overnighter on the way back to Melbourne. Free camping in a park in a tiny town. Windy and Cold, but we got a nice sunset, cooked up a curry and did I mention it was FREE?!

steps.name: South Melbourne
steps.description: Back in the city! 2 weeks house sitting, Grand Prix, James' family visiting, then we'll say goodbye to Melbourne for good (for this trip anyway!)

steps.name: Spring Beach
steps.description: We splashed out an Airbnb with a tennis court for James’ birthday, no regrets, it was amazing.
